               <msContents>
                  <msItem>
                     <note type="general">Catalogue no. 26; Nelson collection no. N283.  Pales, the choachyte, is Muhs&amp;apos; Taxpayer 35.  The usual payment for the burial tax on the interment of one individual in the necropolis in the second half of the reign of Ptolemy III was 7 obols.  Pr ("house" or "estate") is often written in place of the masculine definite article pa with the cardinal directions.  In line 4, r pr imnt "the west" is a rare variation on the phrase r ta khast "to the necropolis," which often follows the phrase r.in=w "who was brought" in burial tax receipts.</note>
                     <note type="general">Location: Oriental Institute</note>
                     <note type="general">Pub. status: Published: recto</note>
                     <note type="lines">On recto: 5 lines in Demotic</note>
                     <note type="paleography">The smudged area in line 4 clearly ends in a vertical stroke, which could be ibd 1; it could also be taken together with the one digit of the year to read 4 rather than 3, but then there would be no month number.  The shape of the initial sign of the season name favors reading peret.</note>
                     <note type="recto_verso">Source of description: On recto: receipt</note>
